iety? The Emergence and Development of Film Schools in Europe -- t12. Institutions of Film Culture: Festivals and Archives as Network Nodes -- t13. The German Reich Film Archive in an International Context -- tNotes on Contributors -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween the two world wars, a distinct and vibrant film culture emerged in Europe. Film festivals and schools were established; film theory and history was written that took cinema seriously as an art form; and critical writing that created the film canon flourished. This scene was decidedly transnational and creative, overcoming traditional boundaries between theory and practice, and between national and linguistic borders. This new European film culture established film as a valid form of social expression, as an art form, and as a political force to be reckoned with. By examining the extraordinarily rich and creative uses of cinema in the interwar period, we can examine the roots of film culture as we know it today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aExperimental filmszEuropexHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAndersson, Lars Gustaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAurich, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuir, Greg de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunning, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagener, Malte, econtributor.4